	   <tr><td colspan=2>As almost anyone else you are stone set in your thinking. Holy trinity, fixed roles for every class, priests don't melee. blah, blah.<br>As stated below, if you have the &quot;ideal&quot; exp group, this might be true and give you the most experience at the lowest risk. But, sadly as you might contend, fortunately as i think, a lot of times you don't always have your favorite group composition.<br>Another example: If you have some space, this is a efficient and fun group: Enchanter, druid, cleric. Druid snares, cleric fears, enchanter controls traffic and gives everyone the mana to make it work.<br>Now, in your world, none of these would ever hit the mob. everyone would med, blast/dot, med etc. Even with clarity, this will not really be that effective. As cleric i will not have to heal much in this situation. If the chanter boons and quickens me, i can do more damage meleeing than i could blasting. The same is true for the druid, one dot up front, then melee.<br>Clarity keeps you close to full even standing up and swinging. Everyone has a blast, exp and money is fair, all is good.<br><br>Now, my estimate i can outdamage my blasts with boon and speed might be a bit off (though i think not), maybe we could get 10% or 15% more exp with only sitting and blasting. But we would be bored to death.<br><br>Maybe the conclusion is: If you want to be uber or 3l33t or only care for phat lewt (dude speak intentional, before someone complains), keep your narrow mindset, do everything according to your fixed set of rules and be happy with that.<br>On the other hand, if you want to have fun, be creative, try stuff, make it work. You might die a few times, have to run a few, whatever. But if you have fun, who cares.<br><br>PS: A lot of the people playing mainly melee classes seem to fail to understand, that they have the good part in exp groups. A well working outside dungeon group is deadly boring for the healers and chanter. Yet they have the full responsibility for anything that can go wrong. Any deaths are caused by cleric, snarer or chanter making a mistake (except for maybe puller errors). So, try to be a little understanding, if some of us sometimes want to break out a bit and have a few whacks, as long as we do our jobs (druids forgetting to snare sets my teeth on edge).<br><br>&nbsp;<br>Nindor<br>L65 Dwarven Cleric on Zebuxoruk<br>Stone</td></tr>
