	   <tr><td colspan=2>Seems like you have some pretty stong convictions here. Your &quot;Druids don't melee&quot; is like 20% of the board content.<br>While i basically concur with it, i think setting your mind in stone is a bad idea. I see so much uncreative repeating of paroles in everquest that sometimes i think thinking is prohibited.<br>My opinion is, do what works. If you can make druid meleeing work in a group, do it. If you can't don't.<br>The axiom &quot;Druids don't melee&quot; is in the same vein as all that holy trinity stuff and fixed roles for every class. True, usually exp is best in a conservative composed group. However, the most fun groups i ever had usually were very unconventional and broke all the normal &quot;rules&quot;. Most of the time we even made decent exp.<br>For example i was once in LOIO with my cleric around 24 or so, and we had the following group: 2 chanters, 3 druids and me as cleric. Incidentally someone had an alt cast Wolf on all of us, but it would not have been necessary (but i could melee much better as cleric). We used that spot a bit past the fort coming from windmills that has tons of wandering mobs. Most fights we had 3-4 adds, often pulled in adds intentionally, feared, DSed, nuked, all meleed, even the chanters. We had enormous fun, made good exp and broke every rule in the book.<br><br>Remeber, we should play Everquest to have fun, not to gain exp and levels. Gaining exp and levels usually is fun, but making it the whole purpose of playing really diminishes the game.<br>&nbsp;<br>Nindor<br>L65 Dwarven Cleric on Zebuxoruk<br>Stone</td></tr>
